.IX Title "Bio::DB::GFF::Adaptor::memory 3"
.TH Bio::DB::GFF::Adaptor::memory 3 "2018-10-02" "perl v5.22.1" "User Contributed Perl Documentation"
.\" For nroff, turn off justification.  Always turn off hyphenation; it makes
.\" way too many mistakes in technical documents.
.if n .ad l
.nh
.SH "NAME"
Bio::DB::GFF::Adaptor::memory \-\- Bio::DB::GFF database adaptor for in\-memory databases
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 5
\&  use Bio::DB::GFF;
\&  my $db = Bio::DB::GFF\->new(\-adaptor=> \*(Aqmemory\*(Aq,
\&                             \-gff    => \*(Aqmy_features.gff\*(Aq,
\&                             \-fasta  => \*(Aqmy_dna.fa\*(Aq
\&                            );
.Ve
.PP
or
.PP
.Vb 3
\&  my $db = Bio::DB::GFF\->new(\-adaptor=>\*(Aqmemory\*(Aq);
\&  $db\->load_gff_file(\*(Aqmy_features.gff\*(Aq);
\&  $db\->load_fasta_file(\*(Aqmy_dna.fa\*(Aq);
.Ve
.PP
See Bio::DB::GFF for other methods.
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This adaptor implements an in-memory version of Bio::DB::GFF.  It can be used to
store and retrieve \s-1SHORT GFF\s0 files. It inherits from Bio::DB::GFF.
.SH "CONSTRUCTOR"
.IX Header "CONSTRUCTOR"
Use Bio::DB::GFF\->\fInew()\fR to construct new instances of this class.
Three named arguments are recommended:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&   Argument         Description
\&
\&   \-adaptor         Set to "memory" to create an instance of this class.
\&   \-gff             Read the indicated file or directory of .gff file.
\&   \-fasta           Read the indicated file or directory of fasta files.
\&   \-dir             Indicates a directory containing .gff and .fa files
.Ve
.PP
If you use the \-dir option and the indicated directory is writable by
the current process, then this library will create a \s-1FASTA\s0 file index
that greatly diminishes the memory usage of this module.
.PP
Alternatively you may create an empty in-memory object using just the
\&\-adaptor=>'memory' argument and then call the \fIload_gff_file()\fR and
\&\fIload_fasta_file()\fR methods to load \s-1GFF\s0 and/or sequence
information. This is recommended in CGI/mod_perl/fastCGI environments
because these methods do not modify \s-1STDIN,\s0 unlike the constructor.
.SH "METHODS"
.IX Header "METHODS"
See Bio::DB::GFF for inherited methods.
